Installing a valid Mercury/32 license entitles you to receive notifications of program updates and security advisories direct from the Mercury development team. The presence of a valid license will enable the controls in this dialog.

Note that enabling notifications will cause Mercury to connect periodically to our servers (sometimes called 'phoning home') - make sure your corporate security policy allows this, and that your firewall allows outgoing access to port 110. For more information, please see the help.
Use the "Filename" button to insert the names of files as targets for "File:", "TFile:", "Daemon:", "Filter:" and "Public:" aliases.
Conversion of Mailing List Subscription Files

Mercury/32 now uses a new format for the files in which information about mailing list subscribers is stored. The new format is incompatible with earlier versions, and is also incompatible with Mercury/NLM v1.48 and earlier versions.
Your existing subscriber files will be automatically converted to the new format when you click the OK button: the original files will be unchanged, and the new versions will have the extension .MLS.
If your lists are currently shared between Mercury/32 and an incompatible version of Mercury/NLM, they will effectively be separated after conversion.
If you click "Exit" now, no conversion will occur, and Mercury/32 will close down.
Error during conversion of Mailing List Subscription Files!
Mercury has encountered a mailing list subscription file in the old format that has the extension .MLF. This extension is reserved for subscription files in the new format.
Mercury has renamed the old version of the file with the extension .V2X and will store the new information in the file with the .MLF extension.

If your lists are currently shared between Mercury/32 and an incompatible version of Mercury/NLM, you will need to edit the Mercury/NLM "List of Lists" file and specify an alternative name for the subscription file.

Generate a set of test messages

Use this dialog to generate a set of test messages in your mail queue. The generated messages are in valid RFC2822 format and will be processed normally by Mercury. This routine is intended for testing purposes only, to allow you to create workload.

Exercise caution when using this option - if you get the address templates wrong, you can inundate some hapless recipient with a flood of seemingly garbage mail. Careless use may also result in your server being blacklisted by some hosts.
(Note: this action is only possible if you are using a network support plugin that supports broadcast messages)
The file you specify must be plain text. You can set the subject field of the message by setting the first line of the file to SUBJECT: followed by the text you want.
Enter the filename to wait for:
IMPORTANT NOTE! Mercury will *delete* this file once it exists. The intention is that a process will create it as a flag to indicate that it has finished.
Mercury will wait a maximum of two minutes for the file to appear.
Enter the header to add to the message:
You must enter the header exactly as it is to appear in the message, including the keyword and ':' character.
Any existing headers of this type will be stripped from the message during this operation.
Enter the filename or directory for saving the attachment
If you enter a filename in this field, Mercury will save the file using that name, overwriting any existing file with that name if necessary.

Alternatively, you can enter an '@' symbol followed by the name of a directory, and Mercury will save the attachment in that directory using the filename encoded in the message. If you use this method, the directory must exist.
In either case, you must supply a full path - there is no 'default directory' for this operation.
Enter directory path for secondary queue

The directory must be specified in a format accessible by Mercury - on networks, you should use the UNC path format. If the queue is on a remote server, it is up to you to ensure that the workstation where Mercury runs is logged into that server with sufficient rights to access the queue.
Edit content control blacklist or whitelist

Each address in the list must appear on a line of its own. You can use '*' wildcards in any address - so, to match all users at 'domain.com', you would enter '*@domain.com'. This editor can handle lists up to 32KB in size: for larger lists, use an external text editor.
